76561198007285414,Not Recommended,313010,14392384,"Posted: 8 February, 2015",all,Hatfullofsky,"TLDR: Close to being such a good game and yet so far away. Overall it comes across as having all the ingredients to be the the greatest city building game ever, and If they fixed some of the flaws it would be great, as it is, I just can't recommend it.I know of the big furore over this game essentially being a poor update on a previously released title ""Cities XL"", but I never bought those games and cannot judge this game against it; this review will just be of the game on its own and in isolation. If anything my comparison point would be ""SimCity 4"", because like most people we've all just been crying out for a sequel to that game that has never happened (at least not how we wanted it, looking at you SimCity Societies).The Good:- You can build a city as pretty as the pictures above, it's all very zen.- The music is quite nice and generally the onscreen notifications aren't overwhelming or irritating.- Gameplay is fairly intuitive with nicely varied levels of difficulty, especially if you're used to the city building game format.- The trading system is balanced meaning specialisation of a city can be done easily, you want to build a tourist paradise or an farming utopia? Knock yourself out, it's a lot of flexibility with how you play.The Bad:- Poor terrain modification tools, the maps look how they look and you'd better like it.- The UI is a little bit clunky, occasionally you'll miss-click things.- Zoom out a little bit and all the vehicles turn to weird grey/black boxes on the road. It upsets your zen greatly.- I can build individual buildings to a style or I can basically pot-luck it with the city zoning, I can't just set a style of building? You crazy.- Roads vs Terrain, being unable to properly terraform the landscape makes this maddening however.- The tutorial thinks it's funny.The Ugly:- This game will crash on you, a lot, regularly.- Lag. Laaaaaaaaggggggg.Verdict:If they got rid of the ugly, you could live with the bad, with both however you end up struggling to play the game, this then magnifies any flaws with the game. Like old Lara Crofts terrible camera angles, or resident evils weird control schemes, you fight with them for a while and then you put the game down and you just never pick it up again."
