,Recommended,313010,14367853,"Posted: 7 February, 2015",all,ThatsMichaelNow,"My Personal Review of Cities XXLFirst off, I put less than 2 hours playing CXLPlatnium, (which I did get on a deep discount), because of it's cam controls. Being able to get the latest version CXXL on a deep discount was a sweet bonus. I was hoping for a cam controls fix or at the very least, a place to adjust the sensitivity of the mouse movement. In spite of the cam controls, I spent no less than 22 hours straight playing once it was finished installing.An immediate reloading of the game from a shut down seems to bring about a downloading of data for the game each and every time it is re-loaded directly after shutting the game down (still looking into this). So, game re-load time is a bit slow. The cam controls are just the same as in CXL but I've decided to just do my best at learning to manipulate the cam and adjust to the super sensitivity of it. Alternatively, there are key commands that can be used to control the camming as well. During the first 20 hours of play, not once did the game ever crash on me. Kudos to the devs for that man. Not withstanding that at the time of posting this review, I found this tip posted by my good gamer buddy Monterico athttp://youtu.be/HQgg1S2OgBINow while I've not put hardly any time into the previous version, there are at least 3 noticeable differences between CXL and CXXL: 1. A whole new interface. Getting use to it was not difficult at all. 2. Adjustable sky options which act sort of like mood filters. The Rainbow and Black Storm are my favorites already. 3. New Maps. Oh yes, the maps are freaking huge and there are some new ones albeit I do not know at the moment which ones they are exactly. In any case, if you didn't like small map sizes in previous city building games, you'll spend a lot of time trying to fill up a map in CXXL.A sinde note here is that of the first 22 hours of game play, it never once crashed on me.The fact that I spent 22 hours straight playing this latest version should tell you a lot about my first impressions of the game. I love being creative but prefer low impact games due to my failing health issues. Use to love shooter games but now, I just like a game I can play while laid back. I was asked often last night while streaming my game play, ""So is it better than SimCity?"" To answer that in a nutshell, no, it is just another city builder style game. Big maps or small, I don't care about that and find that some of the gaming community is a little to stuck up and demanding when it comes to what ""they"" think should or should not be in a game of this style. I enjoyed SimCity a lot and the multi-player online feature was what made the the latest version so much fun. While CXXL does not have multi-player, the shear sizes of the maps should keep me busy for a very long while till ""No Mans Sky"" (the next game I am holding out for) is released at which time you may find my solely playing that exclusively if not permanently. Until then, sorry Maxis/EA, you just lost a loyal fan till you can come out with a bigger, better SimCity. :pI wonder how long it will take to even try to fill up a full map in CXXL. Guess well have to wait and see. Looks like I might have to go after the 10 million population achievment at least."
